            ContentJson = """{"passingScore":80,"questionsPerQuiz":8,"shuffleOptions":true,"showExplanationsAfterSubmit":true,"questions":[{"id":"as1","text":"You've received a new CNC mill from Haas. What is the first step to register it in QB Engineer?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Go to Admin → Equipment and register the serial number"},{"id":"b","text":"Navigate to Assets, click Add Asset, fill in the name, type (Machine), manufacturer (Haas), and location","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Create a Job on the Kanban Board and tag it as equipment setup"},{"id":"d","text":"Add it to Inventory as a new storage location"}],"explanation":"New equipment is registered in the Assets module. Click Add Asset, select type Machine, and fill in the details. The asset starts in Active status by default."},{"id":"as2","text":"A customer sends you a mold they own for production. How do you track this in QB Engineer?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Create an Asset with type Tooling and toggle Customer Owned to ON","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Add it as a Part in the Parts Catalog with status Draft"},{"id":"c","text":"Create a Purchase Order to record its receipt"},{"id":"d","text":"Add it to Inventory as received stock"}],"explanation":"Customer-owned tooling is tracked as a Tooling asset with the Customer Owned toggle enabled. This distinguishes it in reports and ensures proper handling."},{"id":"as3","text":"An asset shows a status of 'Out of Service' (red chip). What does this mean?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The asset is scheduled for routine maintenance next week"},{"id":"b","text":"The asset has been permanently retired and will be sold"},{"id":"c","text":"The asset is broken or otherwise unavailable for use — an unplanned outage","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"The asset's operating hours have exceeded its service life"}],"explanation":"Out of Service (red) indicates an unplanned outage — the asset is broken or unavailable. This is different from Maintenance (yellow, which is planned downtime) and Retired (gray, permanently removed)."},{"id":"as4","text":"You want to see all tooling assets that are currently down for maintenance. How?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Go to Assets, set the Type filter to Tooling and the Status filter to Maintenance","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Run a report in the Reports module filtered by asset status"},{"id":"c","text":"Check the Dashboard maintenance widget"},{"id":"d","text":"Go to Admin → Equipment → filter by status"}],"explanation":"The Assets page has two filters: Type and Status. Set Type to Tooling and Status to Maintenance to see exactly the assets you need."},{"id":"as5","text":"Beyond the Acquisition section (which every asset has), what extra fields appear specifically when you set an asset's type to Tooling?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Warranty Date, Insurance Policy, and Depreciation Rate"},{"id":"b","text":"Customer Owned toggle, Cavity Count, and Tool Life Expectancy","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Operator Assigned, Shift Schedule, and Calibration Date"},{"id":"d","text":"No additional fields — all asset types have exactly the same form"}],"explanation":"On top of the Acquisition & Accounting section that every asset shows, Tooling assets get three extra fields: Customer Owned (toggle), Cavity Count (number of cavities in a mold), and Tool Life Expectancy (expected total shots before replacement)."},{"id":"as6","text":"A tooling asset's Current Shot Count is approaching its Tool Life Expectancy. What does this indicate?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The tool needs to be recalibrated before the next production run"},{"id":"b","text":"The tool is nearing end of life and may need replacement or refurbishment soon","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"The tool has exceeded its warranty period"},{"id":"d","text":"Nothing — shot count is informational only and has no significance"}],"explanation":"When Current Shot Count approaches Tool Life Expectancy, it's a signal that the tool may need replacement or refurbishment. This helps you plan ahead rather than having a tool fail unexpectedly during production."},{"id":"as7","text":"You want to quickly change a machine's status from Active to Maintenance without opening the edit dialog. How?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Click the asset row, then click the Maintenance status button in the detail panel","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"Right-click the row and select Set Status → Maintenance"},{"id":"c","text":"You must open the edit dialog to change status"},{"id":"d","text":"Drag the asset row to the Maintenance section of the table"}],"explanation":"The asset detail panel has quick-action status buttons. Click the row to open the detail, then click the Maintenance button to change status immediately."},{"id":"as8","text":"What happens to an asset's data when you set its status to Retired?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"The record is permanently deleted to free up space"},{"id":"b","text":"The record is archived and hidden from all views"},{"id":"c","text":"The record is preserved with full history — it just won't appear in Active/Maintenance filtered views","isCorrect":true},{"id":"d","text":"Only the name is kept — all maintenance history and details are purged"}],"explanation":"Retired assets are never deleted. The full record (maintenance history, operating hours, tooling details) is preserved for reference and compliance. The asset simply no longer appears in active filters."},{"id":"as9","text":"You need to find the serial number of a specific machine. Where do you look?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"Admin → Equipment → Serial Numbers"},{"id":"b","text":"Assets → click the machine row → Serial Number field in the detail view","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Inventory → Equipment tab → serial lookup"},{"id":"d","text":"Reports → Asset Register → export to CSV and search"}],"explanation":"Click any asset row to open its detail panel. The serial number is displayed in monospace font for easy reading. You can also search for assets by serial number using the search box."},{"id":"as10","text":"A forklift was just serviced. Where in the asset record would you see this maintenance event?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"In the asset's Activity Log tab under recent changes"},{"id":"b","text":"In the Maintenance History section of the asset detail panel — showing schedule name, date, who performed it, hours spent, cost, and notes","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"Under Reports → Maintenance History filtered by asset"},{"id":"d","text":"In the Time Tracking page — maintenance is logged as time entries"}],"explanation":"The asset detail panel has a Maintenance History section that shows all past maintenance events with the schedule name, performed date, technician, hours, cost, and notes."},{"id":"as11","text":"You're registering a new CNC mill (type Machine) and want to record what it cost and how it depreciates. Where do you enter that?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"You can't — cost and depreciation fields only appear for Tooling assets"},{"id":"b","text":"In the Acquisition section of the Add Asset dialog: Acquisition Cost and Depreciation Method, which appear for every asset type","isCorrect":true},{"id":"c","text":"In a separate Accounting module — assets don't store cost"},{"id":"d","text":"In the Notes field as free text"}],"explanation":"The Acquisition & Accounting section (Acquisition Cost, Depreciation Method, Work Center, GL Account) is shown for every asset type, not just Tooling. A machine, a forklift, or a mold all capture acquisition details there."},{"id":"as12","text":"Your shop has an external accounting provider connected. How does the GL Account on an asset get populated?","options":[{"id":"a","text":"It is populated automatically by the accounting sync; you'd type it in manually only in standalone mode","isCorrect":true},{"id":"b","text":"You must always type it in by hand on every asset"},{"id":"c","text":"GL accounts are never stored on assets"},{"id":"d","text":"It is copied from the asset's serial number"}],"explanation":"When an external accounting provider is connected, the GL account is populated by the accounting sync. In standalone mode (no provider), you enter the GL account manually."}]}"""
