        // ── Tracking Asset Downtime (Article) ────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Tracking Asset Downtime",
            Slug = "assets-downtime",
            Summary = "What asset downtime is, how breakdown logging works, and how starting and ending a downtime event differs from the Maintenance status.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 4,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 6,
            AppRoutes = """["/assets"]""",
            Tags = """["assets","downtime","breakdown","maintenance"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Tracking Asset Downtime\n\nWhen a machine breaks down mid-shift, you lose production time you usually want to measure. **Downtime tracking** records each unplanned outage as a discrete event with a start, an end, and a reason — so you can total downtime hours per asset and spot the machines that keep failing.\n\nDowntime is gated by the **CAP-MAINT-BREAKDOWN** capability. If your install doesn't have breakdown tracking turned on, you won't see downtime data and the endpoints return a 'not available' response.\n\n### Downtime vs. the Maintenance Status\n\nThese two are easy to confuse:\n\n- **Maintenance status** (the yellow chip you set from the detail panel) is a *current-state flag*. It tells the team \"this machine is unavailable right now.\" It carries no duration.\n- **A downtime event** is a *time record*. It has a start timestamp, an optional end timestamp, and a reason. While a downtime event is open, the asset is effectively down; when you end it, the clock stops and the elapsed time is captured.\n\nUse the status to signal availability on the shop floor; use a downtime event when you need the *hours* for OEE, reliability, or cost reporting.\n\n### The Lifecycle of a Downtime Event\n\n1. **A machine goes down.** Something fails — a spindle alarm, a hydraulic leak, a power fault.\n2. **Start a downtime log** for that asset, recording the reason. The event is now open (no end time yet).\n3. **Optionally flip the asset's status** to Maintenance or Out of Service so the floor sees it's unavailable.\n4. **The machine comes back up.** End the downtime event — the system stamps the end time and the elapsed hours are now part of the asset's downtime total.\n5. **Set the status back to Active** so the asset is available again.\n\nAn asset can have many downtime events over its life; each is a separate row tied to that asset.\n\n### Where Downtime Data Lives\n\nDowntime events are stored per asset and can be listed for a single asset or across the whole shop. Today the downtime list and the start/end actions are driven through the assets API (the same data the OEE and predictive-maintenance views draw on) rather than a dedicated button on the asset detail panel. That means downtime is typically captured by a supervisor or a maintenance-tech workflow, not by every operator from the asset screen.\n\n### Good Habits\n\n- **Start the event when the machine actually stops, not when you get around to it** — the timestamps are what make the hours meaningful.\n- **Always end the event when the machine is back** — an event left open looks like the machine is still down and inflates downtime totals.\n- **Write a real reason** — \"spindle bearing\" is far more useful three months later than \"broke.\"\n- **Pair it with the status** — downtime event for the hours, Maintenance/Out-of-Service status for the at-a-glance signal.\n\n### Related\n\n- *Asset Maintenance Schedules* — for planned, recurring maintenance (vs. unplanned breakdowns here).\n- *Assets Overview* — for the status chips and the difference between Maintenance, Retired, and Out of Service.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Asset Maintenance Schedules (Article) ────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Asset Maintenance Schedules",
            Slug = "assets-maintenance-schedules",
            Summary = "How recurring maintenance schedules, maintenance logs, and maintenance jobs fit together — plus how to read an asset's maintenance history.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 5,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 7,
            AppRoutes = """["/assets"]""",
            Tags = """["assets","maintenance","schedule","pm"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Asset Maintenance Schedules\n\nPlanned maintenance is the opposite of a breakdown: instead of reacting to a failure, you service the asset on a recurring interval to *prevent* one. Forge models this with three connected pieces — **schedules**, **logs**, and **maintenance jobs**. All of this is gated by the **CAP-MAINT-PM** (preventive/predictive maintenance) capability.\n\n### The Three Pieces\n\n1. **Maintenance Schedule** — a recurring plan attached to an asset (\"grease the ways every 250 hours,\" \"replace the filter every 90 days\"). It defines *what* should happen and *how often*. An asset can have several schedules.\n2. **Maintenance Log** — a record that a maintenance task was actually performed. Each log captures the schedule it satisfied, when it was done, who did it, hours spent, cost, and notes. Logging maintenance is how you close the loop on a schedule and build history.\n3. **Maintenance Job** — when a due maintenance task needs real shop work (a technician, parts, time tracking), you can spin up a Job from the schedule. That Job flows on the board like any other work, and ties the maintenance back to your normal job tracking.\n\n### Who Can Do What\n\nCreating and managing schedules, logging maintenance, and creating maintenance jobs are **Admin / Manager–level actions** (they require CAP-MAINT-PM and the appropriate role). A regular operator can *see* the maintenance history on an asset but typically won't be the one creating schedules. If you don't have the capability or role, the maintenance-management actions won't be available to you.\n\n### Reading an Asset's Maintenance History\n\nThis part is visible to anyone with asset access. Open an asset (click its row to open the detail panel) and scroll to the **Maintenance History** section. For each past maintenance event you'll see:\n\n- **Schedule name** — which plan this satisfied\n- **Performed date** — when it was done (MM/DD/YYYY)\n- **Performed by** — the technician's name\n- **Hours spent** — labor hours, shown as e.g. `2h`\n- **Cost** — parts/labor cost, shown as a dollar amount\n- **Notes** — anything the tech recorded\n\nIf the asset has never been serviced, you'll see an empty state (\"No maintenance logs\") with a wrench icon. This section is read-only — it reflects the logs that have been recorded, it isn't where you create them.\n\n### How It All Connects\n\n- A **schedule** says a task is due. \n- Performing it produces a **log** (which then appears in Maintenance History).\n- If the task needs tracked shop work, it becomes a **maintenance Job**.\n- Operating **hours** (see the Field Reference) are how usage-based schedules know when they're due — keep hours current so intervals fire on time.\n\n### Schedules vs. Downtime vs. Predictive\n\n- **Maintenance schedules** = *planned*, recurring, calendar- or hours-based.\n- **Downtime events** = *unplanned* breakdowns you log after the fact (see *Tracking Asset Downtime*).\n- **Predictive maintenance** = the separate Maintenance area, where the system forecasts likely failures and you can schedule against a prediction. Schedules here are the manual, rule-based counterpart.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Printing & Scanning Asset Labels (Article) ───────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
        {
            Title = "Printing & Scanning Asset Labels",
            Slug = "assets-labels",
            Summary = "How the barcode/QR label widget on the asset detail panel works: copy, print, regenerate, and scanning a label to pull up an asset.",
            ContentType = TrainingContentType.Article,
            EstimatedMinutes = 3,
            IsPublished = true,
            SortOrder = 8,
            AppRoutes = """["/assets"]""",
            Tags = """["assets","barcode","qr","labels","scanning"]""",
            ContentJson = """{"body":"## Printing & Scanning Asset Labels\n\nEvery asset can carry a barcode/QR label so anyone on the floor can identify it and pull up its record by scanning. The label tools live in a small **Barcode** widget inside the asset detail panel.\n\n### Finding the Barcode Widget\n\n1. Go to **Assets**.\n2. Click the asset's row to open its **detail panel**.\n3. Scroll past the status buttons — the Barcode widget sits there, marked with a QR icon and the label \"Barcode.\"\n\n### What the Widget Shows\n\n- **The barcode value** — the asset's code, shown in a monospace `code` style.\n- **A Copy button** — copies the barcode value to your clipboard (handy for pasting into another system).\n- **A QR preview** — a scannable QR image of the value. (In the asset detail panel the widget runs in compact mode, which hides the large QR preview to save space but keeps the value and actions.)\n\n### The Actions\n\n- **Print** — opens the label for printing. Use this to put a physical label on the machine, mold, or vehicle. Labels are generated client-side (bwip-js) so they print at the right size for a label printer.\n- **Regenerate** — issues a fresh barcode for the asset, derived from its natural identifier (the serial number, or the name if there's no serial). Use this if a code was never assigned or you need to reissue one.\n- **Generate barcode** — if the asset has no barcode yet, the widget shows a \"No barcode assigned\" state with a button to generate one (again, from the serial/name).\n\n### Scanning a Label\n\nForge listens for USB barcode scanners and NFC readers globally (keyboard-wedge mode). On the screens wired for it — Parts, Inventory, Kanban, Quality, and the shop-floor clock — scanning routes the value into that page's search or lookup. For assets, the workflow is: **print the label, stick it on the equipment, and scan it from a scan-aware screen** to jump straight to the right record instead of typing a serial number.\n\n### Why Label Your Assets\n\n- **Faster identification** on a crowded floor — scan instead of reading a nameplate.\n- **Fewer wrong-asset mistakes** — the scan resolves to exactly one record.\n- **Cleaner maintenance and downtime logging** — start from the right asset every time.\n\n### Good Habits\n\n- **Set a serial number first** if you can — the barcode is derived from the natural identifier, and a serial is more stable than a name you might rename later.\n- **Reprint after a rename or re-serial** so the physical label matches the record.\n- **Don't regenerate casually** — reissuing a code means the old printed label no longer resolves; only regenerate when you intend to relabel.","sections":[]}"""
        });

        // ── Advanced Reference (Reference) ───────────────────────────────
        await GetOrCreateModule(new TrainingModule
